50|$|In {{amorphous}} silicon this long range order is not present. Rather, the atoms form a continuous random network. Moreover, {{not all the}} atoms within {{amorphous silicon}} are fourfold coordinated. Due to the disordered nature of the material some atoms have a <b>dangling</b> <b>bond.</b> Physically, these dangling bonds represent defects in the continuous random network and may cause anomalous electrical behavior.|$|E
50|$|The {{material}} can be passivated by hydrogen, which bonds to the dangling bonds and {{can reduce the}} <b>dangling</b> <b>bond</b> density by several orders of magnitude. Hydrogenated amorphous silicon (a-Si:H) has a sufficiently low amount of defects to be used within devices such as solar photovoltaic cells, particularly in the protocrystalline growth regime. However, hydrogenation is associated with light-induced degradation of the material, termed the Staebler-Wronski effect.|$|E
